{
    "question_stem": "The function \\(g(x)\\) is defined for all real values of \\(x\\) as \\(g(x) = \\frac{2x - 1}{x + 3}\\).",
    "parts": [
        {
            "part_label": "a",
            "question_text": "State the equations of the asymptotes of the graph \\(y = g(x - 2)\\).",
            "solution_text": "The graph of \\(y = g(x)\\) has a vertical asymptote at \\(x = -3\\) and a horizontal asymptote at \\(y = 2\\).  Replacing \\(x\\) with \\(x-2\\) results in a horizontal translation of the graph 2 units to the right.  The vertical asymptote of \\(y = g(x - 2)\\) is therefore at \\(x - 2 = -3\\), so \\(x = -1\\). The horizontal asymptote is unaffected by a horizontal translation, so it remains \\(y = 2\\)."
        }
